** A New Refutation of Time: Borges on the Most Paradoxical Dimension of E=
xistence (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/19/a-new-refutation-of-tim=
e-borges/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0811216993/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Ddde=
fbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

"If our heart were large enough to love life in all its detail=2C we would=
 see that every instant is at once a giver and a plunderer=2C" the French=
 philosopher Gaston Bachelard wrote in contemplating our paradoxical exper=
ience of time (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/01/18/intuition-of-the-i=
nstant-gaston-bachelard/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) in the ea=
rly 1930s. "It is the insertion of man with his limited life span that tra=
nsforms the continuously flowing stream of sheer change =E2=80=A6 into tim=
e as we know it=2C" Hannah Arendt wrote half a century later in her brilli=
ant inquiry into time=2C space=2C and our thinking ego (https://www.brainp=
ickings.org/2015/12/02/hannah-arendt-the-life-of-the-mind-time-thinking/?m=
c_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . Time=2C in other words =E2=80=94=
 particularly our experience of it as a continuity of successive moments=
 =E2=80=94 is a cognitive illusion rather than an inherent feature of the=
 universe=2C a construction of human consciousness and perhaps the very ha=
llmark of human consciousness.

Wedged between Bachelard and Arendt was Jorge Luis Borges (August 24=2C 18=
99=E2=80=93June 14=2C 1986)=2C that muscular wrangler of paradox and grand=
 poet-laureate of time=2C who addressed this perplexity in his 1946 essay=
 "A New Refutation of Time=2C" which remains the most elegant=2C erudite=
=2C and pleasurable meditation on the subject yet. It was later included i=
n Labyrinths (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0811216993/braipick-2=
0?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worl=
dcat.org/title/labyrinths-selected-stories-other-writings/oclc/260942&refe=
rer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) =E2=80=94 th=
e 1962 collection of Borges's stories=2C essays=2C parables=2C and other w=
ritings=2C which gave us his terrific and timeless parable of the divided=
 self (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/06/borges-and-i/?mc_cid=3Ddde=
fbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/19/a-new-refutation-of-time-borges/?=
mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Borges begins by noting the deliberate paradox of his title=2C a contrast=
 to his central thesis that the continuity of time is an illusion=2C that=
 time exists without succession and each moment contains all eternity=2C w=
hich negates the very notion of "new." The "slight mockery" of the title=
=2C he notes=2C is his way of illustrating that "our language is so satura=
ted and animated by time." With his characteristic self-effacing warmth=2C=
 Borges cautions that his essay might be "the anachronistic reductio ad ab=
surdum of a preterite system or=2C what is worse=2C the feeble artifice of=
 an Argentine lost in the maze of metaphysics" =E2=80=94 and then he proce=
eds to deliver a masterwork of rhetoric and reason=2C carried on the wings=
 of uncommon poetic beauty.

Writing in the mid-1940s =E2=80=94 a quarter century after Einstein defeat=
ed Bergson in their landmark debate (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/12=
/09/the-physicist-and-the-philosopher-einstein-bergson-jimena-canales/?mc_=
cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C in which science ("the clarity of=
 metaphysics=2C" per Borges) finally won the contested territory of time f=
rom the dictatorship of metaphysics=2C and just a few years after Bergson=
 himself made his exit into eternity =E2=80=94 Borges reflects on his life=
long tussle with time=2C which he considers the basis for all of his books=
:

In the course of a life dedicated to letters and (at times) to metaphysica=
l perplexity=2C I have glimpsed or foreseen a refutation of time=2C in whi=
ch I myself do not believe=2C but which regularly visits me at night and i=
n the weary twilight with the illusory force of an axiom.

Time=2C Borges notes=2C is the foundation of our experience of personal id=
entity =E2=80=94 something philosophers took up most notably in the 17th c=
entury (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/10/07/rebecca-goldstein-persona=
l-identity/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C poets picked up in=
 the 19th (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/24/walt-whitman-democrati=
c-vistas-self/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C scientists set=
 down in the 20th (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/08/permanent-pres=
ent-tense-suzanne-corkin-h-m/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C=
 and psychologists picked back up in the 21st (https://www.brainpickings.o=
rg/2016/04/27/time-felt-marc-wittmann/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQ=
ID]) .

Borges compares the ideas of the 18th-century Anglo-Irish Empiricist philo=
sopher George Berkeley=2C chief champion of idealist metaphysics=2C and hi=
s Scottish peer and contemporary=2C David Hume. The two diverged on the ex=
istence of personal identity =E2=80=94 Berkeley endorsed it as the "thinki=
ng active principle that perceives" at the center of each self=2C while Hu=
me negated it=2C arguing that each person is "a bundle or collection of di=
fferent perceptions=2C which succeed each other with an inconceivable rapi=
dity" =E2=80=94 but they both affirmed the existence of time.

Making his way through the maze of philosophy=2C Borges maps what he calls=
 "this unstable world of the mind" in relation to time:

A world of evanescent impressions; a world without matter or spirit=2C nei=
ther objective nor subjective=2C a world without the ideal architecture of=
 space; a world made of time=2C of the absolute uniform time of [Newton's=
] Principia; a tireless labyrinth=2C a chaos=2C a dream.

Illustration by Lisbeth Zwerger for a special edition of Alice in Wonderla=
nd (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/07/07/best-illustrations-alice-in-w=
onderland/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

Returning to Hume's notion of the illusory self =E2=80=94 an idea advanced=
 by Eastern philosophy (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/01/30/d-t-suzuk=
i-essays-in-zen-buddhism/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) millenni=
a earlier =E2=80=94 Borges considers how this dismantles the very notion o=
f time as we know it:

Behind our faces there is no secret self which governs our acts and receiv=
es our impressions; we are=2C solely=2C the series of these imaginary acts=
 and these errant impressions. The series? Once matter and spirit=2C which=
 are continuities=2C are negated=2C once space too has been negated=2C I d=
o not know what right we have to that continuity which is time.

But even the notion of a "series" of acts and impressions=2C Borges sugges=
t=2C is misleading because time is inseparable from matter=2C spirit=2C an=
d space:

Once matter and spirit =E2=80=94 which are continuities =E2=80=94 are nega=
ted=2C once space too is negated=2C I do not know with what right we retai=
n that continuity which is time. Outside each perception (real or conjectu=
ral) matter does not exist; outside each mental state spirit does not exis=
t; neither does time exist outside the present moment.

He illustrates this paradox of the present moment =E2=80=94 a paradox foun=
d in every present moment =E2=80=94 by guiding us along one particular mom=
ent familiar from literature:

During one of his nights on the Mississippi=2C Huckleberry Finn awakens; t=
he raft=2C lost in partial darkness=2C continues downstream; it is perhaps=
 a bit cold. Huckleberry Finn recognizes the soft indefatigable sound of t=
he water; he negligently opens his eyes; he sees a vague number of stars=
=2C an indistinct line of trees; then=2C he sinks back into his immemorabl=
e sleep as into the dark waters. Idealist metaphysics declares that to add=
 a material substance (the object) and a spiritual substance (the subject)=
 to those perceptions is venturesome and useless; I maintain that it is no=
 less illogical to think that such perceptions are terms in a series whose=
 beginning is as inconceivable as its end. To add to the river and the ban=
k=2C Huck perceives the notion of another substantive river and another ba=
nk=2C to add another perception to that immediate network of perceptions=
=2C is=2C for idealism=2C unjustifiable; for myself=2C it is no less unjus=
tifiable to add a chronological precision: the
fact=2C for example=2C that the foregoing event took place on the night of=
 the seventh of June=2C 1849=2C between ten and eleven minutes past four.=
 In other words: I denny=2C with the arguments of idealism=2C the vast tem=
poral series which idealism admits. Hume denied the existence of an absolu=
te space=2C in which all things have their place; I deny the existence of=
 one single time=2C in which all things are linked as in a chain. The deni=
al of coexistence is no less arduous than the denial of succession.

One of Norman Rockwell's rare illustrations (https://www.brainpickings.org=
/2015/11/13/norman-rockwell-huckleberry-finn/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) for The Adventures of Huckleberry Finn

This simultaneity of all events has immense implications as a sort of huma=
nitarian manifesto for the commonness of human experience=2C which Borges=
 captures beautifully:

The vociferous catastrophes of a general order =E2=80=94 fires=2C wars=2C=
 epidemics =E2=80=94 are one single pain=2C illusorily multiplied in many=
 mirrors.

Borges ends by returning to the beginning=2C to the raw material of his ar=
gument and=2C arguably=2C of his entire body of work=2C of his very self:=
 paradox. He writes:

And yet=2C and yet=E2=80=A6 Denying temporal succession=2C denying the sel=
f=2C denying the astronomical universe=2C are apparent desperations and se=
cret consolations. Our destiny =E2=80=A6 is not frightful by being unreal;=
 it is frightful because it is irreversible and iron-clad. Time is the sub=
stance I am made of. Time is a river which sweeps me along=2C but I am the=
 river; it is a tiger which destroys me=2C but I am the tiger; it is a fir=
e which consumes me=2C but I am the fire. The world=2C unfortunately=2C is=
 real; I=2C unfortunately=2C am Borges.

The essay=2C as everything in Labyrinths (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obido=
s/ASIN/0811216993/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C=
 is an exceptional read in its continuous entirety; excerpting=2C fragment=
ing=2C and annotating it here fails to dignify the agile integrity of Borg=
es's rhetoric and the sheer joy of his immersive prose. Complement it with=
 Bertrand Russell on the nature of time (https://www.brainpickings.org/201=
6/05/13/bertrand-russell-mysticism-logic-time/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Virginia Woolf on its astonishing elasticity (https://ww=
w.brainpickings.org/2015/05/04/virginia-woolf-orlando-time/?mc_cid=3Dddefb=
b8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and Sarah Manguso on its confounding=2C comf=
orting ongoinginess (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/03/31/ongoingness-=
sarah-manguso?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .


