** Hidden Figures: The Untold Story of the Black Women Mathematicians Who=
 Powered Early Space Exploration (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/19=
/hidden-figures-margot-lee-shetterly/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQI=
D])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/006236359X/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Ddde=
fbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

"No woman should say=2C 'I am but a woman!' But a woman! What more can you=
 ask to be?" astronomer Maria Mitchell=2C who paved the way for women in A=
merican science (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/08/22/maria-mitchell-e=
ducation-women-in-science/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C adm=
onished the first class of female astronomers at Vassar in 1876. By the mi=
ddle of the next century=2C a team of unheralded women scientists and engi=
neers were powering space exploration (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/=
04/15/the-rise-of-rocket-girls/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) at=
 NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.

Meanwhile=2C across the continent and in what was practically another coun=
try=2C a parallel but very different revolution was taking place: In the s=
egregated South=2C a growing number of black female mathematicians=2C scie=
ntists=2C and engineers were steering early space exploration and helping=
 American win the Cold War at NASA's Langley Research Center in Hampton=2C=
 Virginia.

Long before the term "computer" came to signify the machine that dictates=
 our lives=2C these remarkable women were working as human "computers" =E2=
=80=94 highly skilled professional reckoners=2C who thought mathematically=
 and computationally for their living and for their country. When Neil Arm=
strong set his foot on the moon=2C his "giant leap for mankind" had been p=
owered by womankind=2C particularly by Katherine Johnson =E2=80=94 the "co=
mputer" who calculated Apollo 11's launch windows and who was awarded the=
 Presidential Medal of Freedom by President Obama at age 97 in 2015=2C thr=
ee years after the accolade was conferred upon John Glenn=2C the astronaut=
 whose flight trajectory Johnson had made possible.
https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/19/hidden-figures-margot-lee-shetter=
ly/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Katherine Johnson at her Langley desk with a globe=2C or "Celestial Traini=
ng Device=2C" 1960 (Photographs: NASA)

In Hidden Figures: The Story of the African-American Women Who Helped Win=
 the Space Race (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/006236359X/braipic=
k-20?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.w=
orldcat.org/title/hidden-figures-the-american-dream-and-the-untold-story-o=
f-the-black-women-mathematicians-who-helped-win-the-space-race/oclc/950004=
289&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) )=2C M=
argot Lee Shetterly tells the untold story of these brilliant women=2C onc=
e on the frontlines of our cultural leaps and since sidelined by the selec=
tive collective memory we call history.

She writes:

Just as islands =E2=80=94 isolated places with unique=2C rich biodiversity=
 =E2=80=94 have relevance for the ecosystems everywhere=2C so does studyin=
g seemingly isolated or overlooked people and events from the past turn up=
 unexpected connections and insights to modern life.

Against a sobering cultural backdrop=2C Shetterly captures the enormous co=
gnitive dissonance the very notion of these black female mathematicians ev=
okes:

Before a computer became an inanimate object=2C and before Mission Control=
 landed in Houston; before Sputnik changed the course of history=2C and be=
fore the NACA became NASA; before the Supreme Court case Brown v. Board of=
 Education of Topeka established that separate was in fact not equal=2C an=
d before the poetry of Martin Luther King Jr.'s "I Have a Dream" speech ra=
ng out over the steps of the Lincoln Memorial=2C Langley's West Computers=
 were helping America dominate aeronautics=2C space research=2C and comput=
er technology=2C carving out a place for themselves as female mathematicia=
ns who were also black=2C black mathematicians who were also female.

Shetterly herself grew up in Hampton=2C which dubbed itself "Spacetown USA=
=2C" amid this archipelago of women who were her neighbors and teachers. H=
er father=2C who had built his first rocket in his early teens after seein=
g the Sputnik launch=2C was one of Langley's African American scientists i=
n an era when words we now shudder to hear were used instead of "African A=
merican." Like him=2C the first five black women who joined Langley's rese=
arch staff in 1943 entered a segregated NASA =E2=80=94 even though=2C as S=
hetterly points out=2C the space agency was among the most inclusive workp=
laces in the country=2C with more than fourfold the percentage of black sc=
ientists and engineers than the national average.
https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/19/hidden-figures-margot-lee-shetter=
ly/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Margot Lee Shetterly

Over the next forty years=2C the number of these trailblazing black women=
 mushroomed to more than fifty=2C revealing the mycelia of a significant g=
roundswell. Shetterly's favorite Sunday school teacher had been one of the=
 early computers =E2=80=94 a retired NASA mathematician named Kathleen Lan=
d. And so Shetterly=2C who considers herself "as much a product of NASA as=
 the Moon landing=2C" grew up believing that black women simply belonged i=
n science and space exploration as a matter of course =E2=80=94 after all=
=2C they populated her father's workplace and her town=2C a town whose chu=
rch "abounded with mathematicians."

Embodying astronomer Vera Rubin's wisdom on how modeling expands children'=
s scope of possibility (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/04/18/vera-rubi=
n-interview-women-in-science/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C=
 Shetterly reflects on this normalizing and rousing power of example:

Building 1236=2C my father's daily destination=2C contained a byzantine co=
mplex of government-gray cubicles=2C perfumed with the grown-up smells of=
 coffee and stale cigarette smoke. His engineering colleagues with their r=
umpled style and distracted manner seemed like exotic birds in a sanctuary=
=2E They gave us kids stacks of discarded 11=C3=9714 continuous-form compute=
r paper=2C printed on one side with cryptic arrays of numbers=2C the blank=
 side a canvas for crayon masterpieces. Women occupied many of the cubicle=
s; they answered phones and sat in front of typewriters=2C but they also m=
ade hieroglyphic marks on transparent slides and conferred with my father=
 and other men in the office on the stacks of documents that littered thei=
r desks. That so many of them were African American=2C many of them my gra=
ndmother's age=2C struck me as simply a part of the natural order of thing=
s: growing up in Hampton=2C the face of science was brown like mine.

[=E2=80=A6]

The community certainly included black English professors=2C like my mothe=
r=2C as well as black doctors and dentists=2C black mechanics=2C janitors=
=2C and contractors=2C black cobblers=2C wedding planners=2C real estate a=
gents=2C and undertakers=2C several black lawyers=2C and a handful of blac=
k Mary Kay salespeople. As a child=2C however=2C I knew so many African Am=
ericans working in science=2C math=2C and engineering that I thought that'=
s just what black folks did.

https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/19/hidden-figures-margot-lee-shetter=
ly/?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Katherine Johnson=2C age 98 (Photograph: Annie Leibovitz for Vanity Fair (=
http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2016/08/katherine-johnson-the-nasa-mathe=
matician-who-advanced-human-rights?mc_cid=3Dddefbb8098&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
