l thesis that the continuity of time is an illusion=2C that time exists wi=
thout succession and each moment contains all eternity=2C which negates th=
e very notion of "new." The "slight mockery" of the title=2C he notes=2C i=
s his way of illustrating that "our language is so saturated and animated=
 by time." With his characteristic self-effacing warmth=2C Borges cautions=
 that his essay might be "the anachronistic <em>reductio ad absurdum</em>=
 of a preterite system or=2C what is worse=2C the feeble artifice of an Ar=
gentine lost in the maze of metaphysics" =E2=80=94 and then he proceeds to=
 deliver a masterwork of rhetoric and reason=2C carried on the wings of un=
common poetic beauty.</p><p style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;-ms-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #262626;font-family: Georgia=2C serif;font-siz=
e: 15px;line-height: 175%;text-align: left;">Writing in the mid-1940s =E2=
=80=94 a quarter century after Einstein defeated Bergson in <a href=3D"htt=
p://brainpickings.us2.list-manage.com/track/click?u=3D13eb080d8a315477042e=
0d5b1&id=3Df8c6992c04&e=3Da5eb5cdf67" style=3D"-webkit-text-size-adjust:=
 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #C33737;text-decoration: underline=
;">their landmark debate</a>=2C in which science ("the clarity of metaphys=
ics=2C" per Borges) finally won the contested territory of time from the d=
ictatorship of metaphysics=2C and just a few years after Bergson himself m=
ade his exit into eternity =E2=80=94 Borges reflects on his lifelong tussl=
e with time=2C which he considers the basis for all of his books:</p><bloc=
